The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Calcutta link in twin blasts

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Hyderabad, Sept. 21: Hyderabad blasts suspect Rizwan Gazi, arrested on Monday in Chennai, had fled to Calcutta after his sister Shahi Rafzani was picked up early this month, police said.

 A local court today remanded him in judicial custody till October 5. The 25-year-old had dodged the police in Bangalore and Madurai during the month-long hunt.

 When I came to Calcutta early this month, I met some Bangladeshis who gave me money and shelter for about a week. I returned to the south 10 days ago, a police official quoted Gazi as saying during interrogation. Gazi said he was a regular visitor to Calcutta.

 Gazis profile matches the sketch of the bomber in Lumbini Park, one of the two sites of the August 25 explosions. The other blast took place at Gokul Chat Bhandar. 

 The police said Gazi had confessed to his role in the blasts and to sheltering Huji operatives. But as he was led out of court, Gazi screamed: I am innocent.

 His remand came on a day police chief M.A. Basith said he had information that two men had been given Rs 10 lakh to create trouble during Mondays Ganapati immersion. 

 Fourteen Bangladeshi youths who arrived from Calcutta on the East Coast Express this evening were detained. They were being questioned.




